msDesc.head: The Epistles of Paul with commentary

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. Romani sunt partes

p.note: Top of page in black ink: Kgl Bibl. 1734 års Kat no 12. Theol. in fol.. Middle of the page in black ink: Epistolae Sancti Pauli Apostoli. cum Commentariis et glossis. Below in pencil: Från S.t Légers kapell i Loudun (nära Poitiers) (kapellet tilhörde grefvarnas af Anjou slott; är nu museum).
A small envelope attached to the pastedown in the lower outer corner. The envelope contains parts of an endband in blue yarn.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Parchment over wooden boards. No decoration. , in dark ink: 12; in dark ink: Epistolae Pauli Lat.; remains of a lable; stamped in gold: A 141.
binding.condition: The original spine has been mounted on a support of thick paper. Pieces of brown leather on the spine. No bands visible. Stitching visible on .

provenance.p: According to a note on the manuscript belonged to a chapel dedicated to Saint Legier (Leodegar) in a castle in Loudun.
Brought to Sweden by Queen Christina (possibly bought from Paul Petau's collection) and remained in the Royal library after her abdication.
Listed in Vossius’s catalogue from 1651 (U 202:1) and in the catalogue from 1734 (U 125e) as no 12. Theol. in fol..

layout.note: Main text: Ruling and guidelines in hardpoint. Pricking in margin.

Commentary: The commentary is an intergral part of the page layout with its own guidelines and ruling. When the commentary is at its largest it completley surrounds the main text and has been written on hardpoint ruled lines (two lines for each line of the main text). Leaves with less commentary on them have not always been ruled in this way.

p.note: Upper part of page in faded ink of uncertain date: Ca livre Est de leglise ? de sainct legier du chast- a/et lodun Legier.

A poem in French written by a late-medieval hand in dark ink. The poem is 7 lines long and signed Johannis + an illegible surname. The poem is repeated two more times below, but without signature. The page also contains some doodles and additional lines of text.
Short note by the same or similar hand as the the rest of the text written vertically in the outer margin.
Several lines of glosses have been erased on the middle of the page. The text is still faintly visible.
Note by later medieval hand, 5 lines of text: O uos causidici...ordo supernus.
Notes and scribblings by one or more late-medieval hand in dark ink. Notes both in Latin and French. A note at the bottom of again states that the book belonged to the chapel of Saint Légier.

decoDesc.p: Main text in brown ink, capitals in red or touched with red, rubrics in red.

decoNote.p:
: zoomorph P over 8-11 lines. Every new book is introduced by a complex zoomorph P (in Paulus). These letters are outlined in ink and coloured. Main colours: red, blue, green, and yellow. In some cases, e.g. , only blue and red are used. The motives are zoomorph (mainly dragons) with knotwork and architectural elements (columns, acanthus), sometimes combined and sometimes isolated. Above these large initials smaller plain intials over 2-3 lines (+ extending below the line) in red or blue are usually found. These initials belong to a short introductionary paragraph. On 88v and 93r instead of the plain initials smaller versions of the zoomorph initials are used.
: zoomorph M over 4 lines. Same style of motif and colours as the larger initials.
: Plain initials over 1-3 lines (+ extending above and below the line) in red. : Missing initials. Guide letters in lead, possibly by a later hand.
